Sticky pollen adheres to the fur of visiting animals, transporting genetic material.
Nectar attracts pollinators, providing them with energy while facilitating pollen transfer.
Certain flowers release strong scents to lure specific insect species for pollination.
Vibrating petals can shake pollen loose, aiding the transfer to the stigma area.
Self-pollination occurs when pollen transfers within the same flower or plant.
Scientists count tree rings to estimate the tree's considerable age.
Each annual ring records the tree's growth rate during a specific year.
Wide rings indicate favorable growing conditions, suggesting a robust year.
Narrow rings often suggest periods of drought or limited available water.
Analyzing rings helps researchers study past climate variations and events.
Tree ring analysis provides a valuable timeline of environmental history for science.
The number of rings directly correlates with the elapsed years since germination.
Dendrochronology is the scientific study of tree rings for dating purposes.
