Because the roots are shallow, the plant is vulnerable to drought. Therefore, deep watering is necessary for its survival. If you observe wilting, act quickly.
If the engine temperature exceeds the limit, the car will shut down automatically. Because overheating is dangerous, never ignore the warning lights. Therefore, check your coolant regularly.
Because the data set is unbalanced, the model might be biased. If you train it further, it will perform poorly on minority classes. Therefore, resampling techniques are recommended.
If the circuit is open, no current can flow through the wire. Because the indicator light is off, the connection is likely broken. Therefore, you must test the continuity of the circuit.
Because the evidence is circumstantial, the conclusion is not definitive. If a stronger link were found, the suspect would be implicated. Therefore, more investigation is required before conviction.
If the pressure drops too low, the vacuum seal will fail. Because the container is exposed to altitude changes, the seal must be robust. Therefore, a secondary safety valve is needed.
Because the initial hypothesis failed, we must re-examine the variables. If we change the temperature, the reaction rate might shift. Therefore, systematic testing of new conditions is crucial.
If the dosage is too high, adverse side effects may occur. Because the patient has a history of sensitivity, caution is advised. Therefore, consult a physician before administering the medication.
Because all mammals are warm-blooded, and whales are mammals, therefore whales must be warm-blooded. This is deductive reasoning.
Every swan I have seen is white. Therefore, all swans must be white. This inductive generalization is not always factually certain.
If the premises are true, the conclusion must be true. Because deductive logic guarantees this certainty, it moves from general rules to specific cases.
Observing many instances of correlation suggests a pattern. Therefore, we hypothesize a causal link. Inductive logic builds theories from specific observations.
Because the first five swans were white, we conclude all swans are white. This inductive leap fails when contradictory evidence (black swans) emerges.
If the premise 'A=B' and 'B=C' is accepted, then 'A=C' must logically follow. This chain of reasoning exemplifies deduction.
The sun rose in the east every day I lived. Therefore, it will always rise in the east. This pattern recognition is inductive, but not guaranteed.
Deductive logic starts with general axioms to reach a specific, certain conclusion. Inductive logic predicts probabilities from collected data points.
