The argument commits an ad hominem fallacy: instead of addressing the policy, the speaker attacks the proponent's character. Therefore, the policy's validity remains unproven.
Assuming correlation implies causation is a common fallacy. Just because ice cream sales rise with warm weather, it doesn't mean the heat causes the sales increase.
If all politicians are corrupt, then voting is pointless. This is a hasty generalization, as it overlooks the ethical and dedicated individuals who also participate.
The appeal to emotion fallacy attempts to sway judgment through pity, not logic. Therefore, the argument must be evaluated purely on its factual merits, regardless of emotional impact.
Just because my parents believed X, does not mean X is true. This flawed reasoning is an appeal to authority without proper evidence, invalidating the conclusion.
This argument commits the false dichotomy fallacy by presenting only two choices. There might be viable, third options that the speaker deliberately ignores or suppresses.
Because the CEO was late, he must be in trouble. This is a non sequitur; the lateness, by itself, does not logically necessitate any specific negative outcome.
The slippery slope fallacy suggests a minor action leads to catastrophe. We must examine the actual causal links instead of accepting the exaggerated, worst-case scenario.
