The dentist stressed that sugary snacks contribute significantly to decay. Reducing refined carbohydrates and opting for natural sugars is crucial for strong enamel.
He advised me to chew crunchy fruits and vegetables regularly. The natural abrasive action helps keep teeth clean and stimulates proper saliva production.
We discussed how acidic drinks, even juices, erode tooth enamel over time. Sipping water or plain milk instead is a much better preventive habit.
For optimal dental health, dentists recommend avoiding sticky, sugary candies. These types of sweets get trapped between teeth, promoting plaque buildup.
My hygienist taught me to rinse with water after eating acidic meals. This helps neutralize the pH level and minimizes damage to the enamel surface.
The dental professional emphasized incorporating dairy products into the diet. Calcium and phosphorus found in cheese and yogurt strengthen tooth structure.
She warned against consuming excessive amounts of processed starches. These refined foods lack nutrients and can encourage bacterial growth in the mouth.
To protect against cavities, the dentist suggested a diet rich in Vitamin C. Vitamin C helps the body build and maintain healthy, strong tooth enamel.
