She didn't listen to my warning about the unreliable contractor. She should have taken my advice and hired someone else. If she could have just trusted my judgment, the kitchen renovation would have been flawless. She would have saved thousands of dollars and avoided weeks of stress and frustration.
Looking back at college, I realize I should have joined more clubs. If I could have spent time networking with classmates, I probably would have found a better internship. Instead, I focused only on my grades. It's a lesson in regret, reminding me that sometimes seizing opportunities is more valuable than achieving perfect scores.
When we were younger, we really should have traveled to Southeast Asia. Instead, we stayed home and watched movies. If we could have afforded the trip, we absolutely would have seen incredible temples and beaches. Now, seeing photos online, we wish we had been more adventurous and planned something grander.
She often muses about the job she turned down years ago. She should have accepted the promotion; it was a huge opportunity. If she could have moved to the city, her career trajectory would have accelerated dramatically. Now, she knows that hesitation cost her time, making her reconsider her past choices.
The old photograph always reminds him of the conversation he didn't have. He should have confronted his friend about the misunderstanding. If he could have spoken up at the time, they might have cleared the air. Instead, he let pride guide him, and now the silence feels heavier than any argument could ever be.
Before moving here, I should have researched the local transport system better. I could have spent more time reading reviews and taking a tour. If I could have arrived knowing the optimal routes, I would have saved so much money and stress. Now, navigating this complex city feels like a continuous, frustrating puzzle.
