A study might show that people who own more books also donate more. This correlation might actually be caused by a third factor: higher socioeconomic status.
Simply observing two variables change together does not prove one causes the other. Correlation only suggests a potential relationship, requiring deeper investigation.
Mistaking correlation for causation is a common logical fallacy. Just because A and B happen simultaneously, A doesn't necessarily cause B.
We must be careful not to assume a causal link just because historical data shows a pattern. Coincidence can easily be mistaken for a genuine cause-and-effect relationship.
The observed link between coffee consumption and productivity needs scrutiny. Perhaps the underlying cause is the early morning routine, not the caffeine itself.
Researchers must control for confounding variables when analyzing data. Establishing true causation requires experimental design, not just observational correlation.
While the correlation between screen time and poor sleep is noted, it is crucial to determine if the lack of sleep causes poor focus, or vice versa.
